<subSubSection id="C3093ADC036D1979FF0BF911FE4BFACF" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="79" pageId="3" pageNumber="76" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BAC6957036D197CFF0BF911FB90F8E0" blockId="3.[136,1452,1752,2031]" box="[136,1073,1788,1815]" pageId="3" pageNumber="76">
Etymology: 
<emphasis id="B967B545036D197CFE8FF911FE6DF8E0" box="[268,460,1788,1814]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="76">
— 
<taxonomicName id="4C1312D4036D197CFEAAF911FE6DF8E0" authorityName="Yang-Yang Cui, Qing Cai &amp; Zhu L. Yang" authorityYear="2022" box="[297,460,1788,1814]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Amanitaceae" genus="Amanita" kingdom="Fungi" order="Agaricales" pageId="3" pageNumber="76" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="pallidoverruca">pallidoverruca</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
refers to the dirty white to greyish warts on the pileus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAC6957036D197CFF3EF8CDFE8FF874" blockId="3.[136,1452,1752,2031]" pageId="3" pageNumber="76">
Diagnosis:— 
<taxonomicName id="4C1312D4036D197CFED2F8CDFDFCF8CC" authorityName="Yang-Yang Cui, Qing Cai &amp; Zhu L. Yang" authorityYear="2022" box="[337,605,1824,1850]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Amanitaceae" genus="Amanita" kingdom="Fungi" order="Agaricales" pageId="3" pageNumber="76" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="pallidoverruca">
<emphasis id="B967B545036D197CFED2F8CDFDFCF8CC" box="[337,605,1824,1850]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="76">Amanita pallidoverruca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related and similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C1312D4036D197CFC48F8CDFB9DF8CC" box="[971,1084,1824,1850]" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Amanitaceae" genus="Amanita" kingdom="Fungi" order="Agaricales" pageId="3" pageNumber="76" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="excelsa">
<emphasis id="B967B545036D197CFC48F8CDFB9DF8CC" box="[971,1084,1824,1850]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="76">A. excelsa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs from the latter by its more robust basidioma, dirty white to greyish volval remnants on the pileus, and the greyish yellow to olivaceous edge of the annulus.
</paragraph>
